        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-12-20T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-12-20T20:00:00-05:00" n="448"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d448">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.<gloss target="#t_BC1">BC</gloss>
                    Indonesia/12–2048: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Consulate General at Batavia</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d448fn1">Repeated in telegram 4883, December 21, 3 p. m., to
                        Paris (for Jessup).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-12-20T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 20, 1948—8 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>676. <gloss target="#t_Usgoc1">Usgoc</gloss> 255. Following communiqué will be
                    released for publication in US afternoon papers Tuesday Dec 21:<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d448fn2">The communiqué was announced by the Acting Secretary of
                        State at his press conference on December 22 and issued by <gloss
                            target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> at the same time.</note>
                </p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“<gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> Administrator announced today that
                        effective immediately <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> is suspending the
                        issuance of authorizations for the procurement <pb facs="0607" n="593"
                            xml:id="pg_593"/> of supplies destined to be used in Indonesia. Hitherto
                            <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> has allotted funds for economic
                        recovery of the Dutch-held portion of Indonesia as part of its program for
                        assistance to the Netherlands. This policy was based on the conviction that
                        expansion of production and exports of the many raw materials of Indonesia
                        such as rubber, copra, palm oil, tin, petroleum, bauxite, etc. would provide
                        a great stimulus to the recovery of not only the Netherlands, but also of
                        Western Europe as a whole. Up to the present <gloss target="#t_ECA1"
                            >ECA</gloss> has earmarked $72,700,000 for Indonesia. Of this sum,
                        $4,100,000, represents a procurement authorization issued during the third
                        quarter of 1948 for the purchase of copra in Indonesia on behalf of the
                        Bizone. Against the balance of $68,000,000 <gloss target="#t_ECA1"
                            >ECA</gloss> has issued procurement authorizations totaling $59,573,358.
                        Of this amount well over half has been for textiles, rice and wheat flour
                        which have not only provided an incentive to increased production but have
                        directly benefited the Indonesian population. As previously indicated, no
                        procurement authorizations have been issued for military supplies.</p>
                    <p>
                        <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> funds can only be spent if there is
                        reasonable assurance that their expenditure will actually contribute to
                        economic recovery. In view of developments in Indonesia in recent days
                            <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> considers that conditions favorable
                        to the continuation of an effective economic assistance program do not now
                        exist. The further commitment of <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> funds
                        would therefore be unjustified.</p>
                    <p>This decision to suspend the Indonesian program has been concurred in by the
                        Department of State.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
